WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Right, so we've got our basic Shiny navbar page, and pretty much any navbar page that

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:28.040
you've seen, you've probably noticed that you're constricted to the fact that each one

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:35.720
of these tab links has to link to content inside of that page. So we haven't really

00:00:35.720 --> 00:00:41.799
provided you with a way to like officially provide another link here that maybe links

00:00:41.799 --> 00:00:51.919
to some external website. Or what if you wanted to like have a right aligned nav item that

00:00:51.919 --> 00:00:58.040
links to like a login page or something like that. Historically, there's been no way to

00:00:58.040 --> 00:01:06.879
do this officially with Shiny. So I've seen people come up with pretty crazy hacks to

00:01:06.879 --> 00:01:15.000
make this possible, which was part of the motivation for doing this in the first place.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:22.239
But bslib, you know, provides this new API, essentially, that replaces tab panel, and

00:01:22.239 --> 00:01:28.400
navbar page and navbar menu, kind of the basic building blocks that you may have used to

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:36.160
create a navbar page or a tab set panel or something like that. So with the new interface,

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:42.800
it's called, instead of tab panel, you say nav, give it a title, give it some content.

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:49.160
There's also a nav item, it basically just takes whatever you give it, and places it

00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:56.160
directly in that nav heading. So you could do something like provide a hyperlink to Shiny's

00:01:56.160 --> 00:02:05.919
GitHub page, or wherever you want to provide a link to. There's actually also ways of using

00:02:05.919 --> 00:02:15.720
this to include something like text input box, which would allow you to implement something

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:20.720
like a search feature in your Shiny app, where somebody could type in like in the navbar

00:02:20.720 --> 00:02:24.800
at the top, they could search for something. And then you could wire that up to some server

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:32.320
logic to like show something as people are typing, something like that. There's also

00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:40.440
this nav spacer, where it's kind of like the name suggests, it just adds spacing in

00:02:40.440 --> 00:02:48.679
between like one set of nav items and another set of nav items. So by putting the nav spacer

00:02:48.679 --> 00:02:54.559
here, this will basically left align all of this, all of these, like the A and the B and

00:02:54.559 --> 00:03:03.399
the Shiny external link. And then it will right align this nav menu that has other like,

00:03:03.399 --> 00:03:07.919
you know, links to more content within the page, and then another nav item to link to

00:03:07.919 --> 00:03:18.160
some other external content. And this is kind of a fancy way of reducing duplication for

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:28.080
example, where this nav items function will return a list of these nav items, essentially,

00:03:28.080 --> 00:03:38.259
so that I can use this rlang splicing operator to essentially splice in the list of nav items

00:03:38.259 --> 00:03:46.000
into this navbar page. There's also another argument to navbar that allows you to, like

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:53.320
if you have some content that you want to show regardless of what nav item is selected

00:03:53.320 --> 00:03:58.639
in a navbar page, you can use, there's a header and a footer to say like, always show this

00:03:58.639 --> 00:04:08.039
content, like above or below the other content that is dependent on whatever tab is selected.

00:04:08.039 --> 00:04:14.279
So I'm using that to also show these other functions that can consume a collection of

00:04:14.279 --> 00:04:22.000
nav items called navs tab, navs pill. So these two functions essentially replace tab

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:32.679
set panel for, you know, creating that basic like tab look, or also with pills. And there's

00:04:32.679 --> 00:04:40.760
also variants on these called navs tab card and navs pill card, which I'll just show you

00:04:40.760 --> 00:04:47.519
how these actually look. So here's the first navs tab here. So this is like, you know,

00:04:47.519 --> 00:04:54.519
the kind of classic tab set panel look that we're used to seeing everywhere with the ability

00:04:54.519 --> 00:05:00.079
to flip through the tab A and tab B content. I also have this shiny link here, which will

00:05:00.079 --> 00:05:08.320
take me to shiny's GitHub page, as well as the right aligned menu with the other external

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:15.359
link and some other content. So I've taken the same nav items essentially and placed

00:05:15.359 --> 00:05:21.160
them inside of this page navbar to get the top level A and B content. So I can flip back

00:05:21.160 --> 00:05:26.600
and forth here. And then this is the footer content with those other sort of variants

00:05:26.600 --> 00:05:35.600
for rendering a collection of nav items. So here's the navs tab, the navs pill. I do like

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:42.399
this kind of a little bit generally better than the basic tab set panel look in general.

00:05:42.399 --> 00:05:51.760
But I think part of the reason why like tab set panel doesn't always look great is the

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:59.600
fact that there is no padding between this content here and the border. And there's also

00:05:59.679 --> 00:06:06.640
border doesn't extend around the content either. So it kind of looks like there's content sort

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:14.959
of floating in space. And it's also smashed together. So that's why we've provided this

00:06:14.959 --> 00:06:22.559
navs tab card and navs pill card to add some border around all of the content and add some

00:06:22.559 --> 00:06:33.359
padding between that like top border and the actual content inside. So for all sort

00:06:33.359 --> 00:06:38.640
of functional purposes, these provide the same sort of functional experience. But this is just

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:43.279
designed in a slightly different way where it has like a real container around it.

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:51.119
It has sort of a real header to it in the sense that it's got this gray background

00:06:51.359 --> 00:06:58.880
around holding the tabs and the pills. And you may have seen something like this already with

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:07.040
I believe in Shiny, this is called nav list panel. But I'm now calling it navs pill list.

00:07:08.559 --> 00:07:13.679
And there might be like in the future, there might be other different variants that like render

00:07:14.320 --> 00:07:21.040
things in slightly different ways. But this is kind of like more of like a sidebar kind of

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:28.720
approach where you can get those nav items stacked vertically and then the content on the right.

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:35.279
So yeah, and actually, these functions are now used by Shiny underneath the hood when you use

00:07:35.279 --> 00:07:42.559
tab panel or nav bar page. So now the actual logic for all of that stuff lives inside of BS lib.

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:51.760
But we've also like sort of built out the API to allow you to do more with it and sort of

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:56.320
design this functional interface to allow us to

00:07:56.320 --> 00:08:06.559
continue building like more ways to render navigation items, essentially.

